ly been associated with a fear that they will transform humanity beyond recognition, doing away with the very subjects who should receive justice in a transformed world. Further, he shows how utopian writing speaks to contemporary debates about immigration, labor, and other global justice issues. Along the way, Inventions of Nemesis connects utopia to the Greek concept of nemesis, or indignation at a wrong ordering of things, and advances fresh readings of dozens of writers and thinkers—from Plato, Thomas More, Nathaniel Hawthorne, Edward Bellamy, Charlotte Perkins Gilman, and H. G. Wells to John Rawls, Robert Nozick, Fredric Jameson, Ursula Le Guin, Octavia Butler, and Chang-Rae Lee.Ambitious and timely, Inventions of Nemesis offers a vital reconsideration of what it really means to imagine an ideal society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aUtopiasxPolitical aspects. 0aUtopiasxSocial aspects. 0aUtopias. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Subjects & Themes / Politics .2bisacsh  aAldous Huxley.  aB. F. Skinner.  aBlithedale Romance.  aCharles Fourier.  aChernyshevksy.  aDispossessed.  aJonathan Swift.  aLooking Backward.  aMargaret Atwood.  aRepublic.  aThomas Hardy.  aarrangement.  aauthenticity.  aconditioning.  adystopia.  aglobal justice.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary utopias.  amigration.  amobility.  anomos.  aphilosophical utopias.  asocial engineering.  aunderstanding utopia.  autopian history.  autopian ideas.  autopian studies.  autopian thought.  autopian visions.  aworkers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultu